Unsupervised Machine Learning - Clustering using K- Means¶

K-Means clustering is an unsupervised learning technique that is suitable for working with unlabelled data that lacks predefined categories or groups.

The primary objective of this algorithm is to group similar data points together with the number of groups determined by the value of K.

The algorithm follows an iterative approach and assigns each data point to one of the K groups based on the features that are provided.

# I am creating age group 

def age_bracket(age):
    if age <= 30:
        return 'Youths (<30)'
    elif age <= 50:
        return 'Middle age (30-50)'
    else:
        return 'Older adults'

data['age_bracket'] = data['Age'].apply(age_bracket)

def annual_income(income):
    if income <= 40:
        return 'low income (<40)'
    elif income <= 70:
        return 'middle income (40-70)'
    elif income <= 100:
        return 'high income (70-100)'
    else:
        return 'wealthy'

data['annual_income'] = data['Annual_Income_(k$)'].apply(annual_income)

After applying the K-means clustering algorithm, i can determine the optimal number of clusters by using the Elbow Method. This Method involves plotting the "Withing Clusters Sum of Squares (WCSS)" against the number of clusters (K) and selscting the value of K where the rate of decrease in WCSS slows down significantly. In the graph below, I can observer that after the K=3, there is no significant decrease in the WCSS, indicating that the 3 is the optimal number of clusters in this case. Although, the optimal value of K may not always be apparent from the graph, with practice, it becomes easier to identify the elbow point where the rate of decrease in WCSS slows down significantly.

https://www.google.com/url?sa=i&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fpulse%2Ffinding-optimal-number-clusters-k-means-through-elbow-asanka-perera&psig=AOvVaw3aiejmZysd1fgve3-hGtv8&ust=1690655014401000&source=images&cd=vfe&opi=89978449&ved=2ahUKEwikpuvtgrKAAxUFpicCHQrYBUQQr4kDegUIARD3AQ

# How many clusters do i want to create? 
# I will deploy the ML to choose the clusters best for the data using the ELBOW METHOD 

wcss = []
for i in range (1,11): # range of 1 to 10
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters =i, init='k-means++', random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(data1)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_) 

#visulised 

plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss, color = 'red', marker = 'o')
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()

Here, there are two sets of low income earners 'purple' and 'yellow' and there spending score really differ. Part of them have a high spending score while the purple are low spenders.

The middle income earners in green color have a middle spending score as well

The high income earners 'torquoise' and 'blue' are divided into two segments. The 'Blue' category have a high score while the 'torquorise' have a low spending score

Hence, we have a clusterings

The silhouette score of 0.44493777835059417 indicates that the clusters are moderately well-separated
